snippet.textDisplay: I really hate the sequels more than the prequels because the prequels expanded on the star wars story, whereas the sequels erased the star wars story. Instead of expanding on a story we knew little about, it took stories from our childhood and told us they never existed, they're legends. The solo twins, Mara Jade, Luke's New Jedi Order, they never existed, instead this new stuff with Rey and Kylo Ren happened everything else were legends. It didn't help that fans weren't really responsive to the movies either with TFA being very derivative and TLJ being very divisive. So in this situation where we have stories that fans loved being replaced by seemingly inferior stories, the sequels were bound to be more hated. It doesn't help that its missing something the prequels had, expanded universe material. While the films were hit or missed, the stories in the prequels were propped up by the Dark Horse Comics, tv shows, and video games. Instead of that, we have malicious EA games and Disney seems to be focused on making EU books and shows during the original trilogy era with very few Sequel era material.

snippet.textDisplay: it's so refreshing to see someone with the same take I have. All these movies have their moments (some of which are excellent) but as a whole the trilogy is a cohesive mess.  My biggest issue with the TLJ was that there was only one movie left...and TLJ failed as a sequel to TFA  by discarding all of the points and questions it built toward without bothering to directly raise  compelling new issues so there was no forward thrust to the next film leaving JJ,  as you point out, to have to waste time inventing a conflict rather than just continuing the story.  I was hoping JJ and crew would find a way to concoct something that would fix the disconnect between the first two films and that viewing ROS would fill in the gaps and enhance and enrich had happened before.  To me that did not happen... The Emperor's return to me actually makes Luke's actions and exile in TLJ , and his whole arc in the films, make LESS sense...and ultimately cheapens the finale of the original trilogy.

snippet.textDisplay: Your little soapbox talk is something I have been saying for years now basically so I am totally with you on that. I think so many people hold these sorts of franchises to a standard that you will never be able to accomplish because of things like the rose coloured glasses of youth and nostalgia for example. So many have such a deep connection with these stories that get muddled with memories and fandom related facts and community that it is hard divorce those feelings from the entity as a whole. When you cannot divorce the fact that sometimes the stories told or the directions taken are not where your heart or brain think it "needs" to be you are, I feel, doing more harm than good within this microcosm of the built world and community. Sometimes storytellers make mistakes. Sometimes the direction taken is a misstep or hard to see in the big picture because of your proximity to it in that space and time. Sometimes studios try and rewrite or recon things in order to actually be more inclusive or right wrongs of the past. Just because these things happen doesn't mean the stories told that you love are tarnished. It doesn't mean there will always be mistakes or issues. It just means that this time those directions, story points, risks, etc didn't pay off this time. That is it.

snippet.textDisplay:
After seeing the movie, I have to say I respectfully disagree with the "two beginnings" statement. The trilogy is a passing the torch/metatextual meditation of the series and Jedi as a whole.


Episode VII: Call to adventure and assuming the roles.
Episode VIII: Conflict rises, and assumed roles are challenged. Things are going to work out like it seemed. Heroes can come from anywhere.
Episode IX: Banding together, your blood line doesn't define you, the torch is passed.

snippet.textDisplay:
The Maldaloran is the Live-Action Star Wars series the Fans and the Franchise needed and deserved. It still aint flawless but it does everything well that the New Trilogy fails at.

Provides Mando as an good lead character. His orgin, past and even face is a complete mystery but he still manages to be an interesting character you want to follow. In the first episode we hear people how skilled and badass he is and we see it in action. But we see that every fight is a stuggle when the odds are agaist him. When he comes out victorious it feels EARNED. Plus the supporting cast actullay feel important to the plot.

A series that still mains very respectful to the lore set by the series. It is a story that could even feel like it came out of the original trilogy era. Yet it expands and adds new things that still feel like they could easilty fit in with the establaished lore and plot.

Also. Baby Yoda. The Wars Frachise tried to shoehorn in more cute mascot characters each movie now. But none will ever beat Baby Yoda

It’s got a lot of problems that stem from “fixing” the problems of TLJ and it makes leaps of logic to do that rather then bouncing off those plot points. But in the end I enjoyed the movie and seeing these characters’ conclusions especially for Rey and Ben. I honestly can’t believe how people say this is “the worst Star Wars movie” or why it’s even necessary to compare them in that way but i have to disagree with those people.

The ROS had to explain away everything from TLJ whole trying to progress the story and it just flat out doesn’t work.

snippet.textDisplay: Can normally resonate with Chris' reviews which is why after I watch an anticipated movie I will head to his channel to compare notes, but you missed the point on this one Chris, hopefully your second watch will help you work it out. The problem with this trilogy is quite literally the fan base, 7 was an excellent movie, but because of a niche disgruntled fan base they completely altered the direction and let Rian decimate what was originally a great premise to the trilogy. 8 was a joke, how the script even made it past pre-production is just mind boggling, and it was because of a knee jerk reaction to disgruntled fans who expected far too much. If every movie franchise was to directly change their original goals based on a small fraction of negative feed back then hell we'd never see anything cohesive get put together. The fact that J. J. was able to recover this trilogy after how badly Rian trashed it for the sake of 'trying to be different' is amazing. Considering what he had to follow from, this movie was an incredible feat, and a perfect ending to the trilogy of trilogies, brought full circle in so many ways. Chris, you missed too much from this movie on your first watch, clearly because you couldn't check your expectations. If it seemed messy, it was only because J. J. had to fit two movies into one. Apart from the build up of Rey and Kylo's force connection and the passing of Luke, this movie renders 8 obsolete and pointless. J. J. had to complete a 9 part epic story following one of one the worst big budget movies ever made, and he nailed it. He retconned 8 and made his own trilogy and nobody even realised, even Chris as it would seem.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is my review and just my opinion, but will be very honest.


For whoever expected this last movie of the saga to be epic after seeing the two previous failures I must say you are being foolish. Now if you are one of those who just wanted it to be not as bad as the other two then you will get the movie you are expecting.


Couple of things regarding the story:


1) Is on track and not very difficult to understand, it has a few plot holes but that all was caused by the way the previous two films were handled.
2) It is quite entertaining but lacks of an epic ending.


[SPOILER ALERT]
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The story is based on a Ray worried to become what she fears the most, a Kylo wanting to kills the emperor as he posses a threat to Ray and his new empire, and a Palpatine on life support wanting to return as the true emperor of the galaxy and blablablanot gonna go into too much details.


The ending is quite touching but not impressive, in fact it seems they didn't plan for a closure of the story, more like their plan was to keep making SW films but where suddently forced to ended at episode 9. I am not quite happy with the way Palpatine ended, felt like he is so powerful but not powerful at all (you will understand better once you watch the movie).


Overall, the film, story, acting, characters where more entertaining and better organized than the previous two films I could say SW: EPISODE 9 is the best of the new saga (episode 7 and 8).


I will be generous and give it a 7/10.
